column64: A thaw - Snow, which was but little, gone and ground bare. Thus far scarcely any sleighing. Slight Aurora
Fine sleighing and the first this winter here
Aurora Borealis. Appeared first 7:30 o'c. Quite brilliant, very dark below the arch.
Aurora Brilliant Formed first in the shape of an arch. Hazy. The convex side a few degrees south of Cassiopeia.  10 o'c very long hazy streamers splending north of the north star.
column65: A few hazy patches in the south. Motion of beams from W to E. Wind strong from the NW. No clouds that part of the sky not covered by the Aurora very clear.
column66: No dark cloud below the arch. At 10 1/2 a long red streamer a little to the SE.

column64: Aurora Borealis. Appeared first about 8 o'c not very brilliant. 9 1/4 Bright arch in the south about 30 0 long visible [illegible] most of the evening
column65: This arch would at one time shine brightly and in a few seconds [illegible] out to brighten up in a few more seconds.
column66: Shooting stars numerous. Several quite bright meteors seen 10 to 8 very bright meteor, not  seen till near the horizon. a bright curved streak of light was then visible extending from NW to NE
column67: an straight line drawn from the north western [illegible] to the meteor making an angle with the horizon of about 10 o'c two very brilliant meteors. Both fell from Gemini to Orion.
column68: The first which was the most brillilant left a bright streak which was visible for several seonds. 10 to 12 Brilliant meteor. Small shooting stars numerous through the whole evening

column64: Mirage. The mountains to the north of the Basin of Minas appeared very distorted in some parts inverted in the air. This continued through nearly the whole afternoon.
Between 7 and 8 o'c Apr. two peals of thunder were heard to the south.
6 1/4 AM Rainbow Very beautiful 5 to 9 AM Clap of thunder to the NW. Cloud moving to the NE

Aurora. A bank of clouds extending from the horizon about one third of the distance to the North Star so obscured it but little could be seen. The convex side reached about one half the distance from the horizon to the N. Star.
Aurora obscured by clouds reaching from the horizon nearly to the polestar. Aurora faint like the dawn, the convex side of the bands of light touched the polestar at 9:00.
Very fine clouds in the morning cir. and cir. cu. Aurora obscured by clouds
Aurora obscured by clouds. At about 7:30 pm a red rainbow caused by the red rays of the setting sun shining through a mist.
Very faint aurora. At 10:30 a low and very dim arch.
Aurora obscured by clouds. Appeared first about 8:15. At 10 past 11 very dim and hazy.
Aurora. Quite brilliant. Appeared first about half past 8. Obscured by the brightness of the moon by clouds and a thick haze through which the stars shone very dimly.
Aurora. Faint, commenced about 9:00. Thick haze. Atmosphere very smoky.
No clouds but atmosphere very smoky.
Shooting stars quite numerous in all parts of the heavens. Falling to the south at an angle of from 30 deg to 45 deg
2 o'c PM Thunder storm two or three miles to the north with heavy rain. none at Wolfville. A thunder storm came up from the west and passed over at about 21 1/2 o'c PM.
column65: Rain very heavy. Lightning very sharp. generally zigzag, not very frequent. Thunder very heavy. Generally wih two or three distinct explosions like the discharge of heavy guns
column66: and then a heavy crashing echo. Near New Moines a village about 4 or 5 miles to the westward of Wolfville a field of potatoes was destroyed
column67: or blighted by the lightning and persons in the vicinity were thrown down. Oxen were killed at Little Chester to the south of Wolfville.
column68: This storm is said to have been the heaviest that has occurred of many years

column64: Aurora. Fine but very much obscured by clouds. Portions of arches beams etc seen, tinged with red and green.
column65: 10 o'c hazy like the dawn. obscured by clouds.

column64: Aurora. Faint below as stratum of cloud splinding from the horizon south ward to  	within 4 or five miles of Wolfville. Not very bright. Distant lightning.
Such fine aurora streamed by couds
Vivid lightning in the West and South-West.
Vivid lightning in the N-N-W and ESE. In both cases the clouds were below the horizon. Shooting stars numerous, from all parts of the heavens and at all angles in the horizon.
4 o'c AM till daylight quite fine aurora. A comet visible, was seen at Gaspereaux the morning before. PM, Aurora, formed soon after twilight arch very high, obscured by clouds.

At about 5 1/2 PM a cloud came up from the SW. Lightning [illegible] but very vivid. Thunder  very heavy, continued all through the evening. Towards the middle of the night another  cloud passed over [illegible] from which direction, with very vivid Lightning and very heavy thunder.
Aurora, obscured by several patches of cir st clouds where glimpses [ripped][illegible] it showed a low, compact, well defined arch four or five
column65: degrees from [ripped] the space below being very dark. A few long, bright streamers extended nearly to the N Star on account of the clouds
column66: cannot say when it commenced nor when it disappeared. Tehre was a pretty smart breeze blowing at the time from the W.

column64: Aurora, not fine. appeared first soon after sunset, at 7 1/2 PM quite a fine arch, brilliant. 9 o'c hazy

Very fine aurora. Appeared first soon after sunset, sky then obscured by a thick haze through which the stars shone by dimly. A few minutes before 6 o'c PM an arch formed about halfway between the horizon and NS
column65: composed of short briliant beams which were very active, and now and then shooting up long streamers to the zenith in bright detached pa[ripped] with all the colors of the rainbow.
column66: At 10 past 6 streamers shot up from all parts of the heavens to a point about 3 0 south of the zenith, showing a bright light with bright patches of green, red and yellow.
column67: The display lasted but for a minute or so [ripped page] as they flowed in to the central point - had a peculiar throbbing motion.
column68: This [ripped page] seemed to have exhausted itself in the onset. for the rest of the evening it was very faint [ripped] hazy

column64: Solar Halo, between 2.30 to 3.25 o'c P.M. Hazy.

N.B. During the storm of the 22nd the tides rose remarkably high in the Basin of Minas flooding the dyked marshes. I am told by a person who was there at the time that, the same storm and high tide took place at Halifax N.S. the night before.

column31: Obs. notes below sheet indicate many snow storms prevented cloud readings and wind dir.

column64: Fine aurora Commenced early in the eve. Tinged red. noticed that several streams originating near the concave edge of the bank 'a' were of a light yellow color until they came
column65: out at the upper edge of the bank when they were of a deep red color. Slightly cloudy, brisk wind from the NW.

column64: Aurora. Low arch, hazy, some what red, strong wind.
Slight Aurora. Low hazy bank, commenced at 8 o'c
Aurora, faint. Commenced about 8 o'c, low concentric arches.
Aurora. Commenced about 8 o'c, hazy, diffused, a few patches in the southern sky at 11 o'c fine shining.
Aurora, commenced about 8:30 o'c, arches very high both in northern and southern sky, hazy.

column31: Black bird turdus merula? [sic] first seen.

column64: Slight Aurora, long hazy streamers originating near horizon

column31: cypripredium acaule in bloom | Arum in bloom

column64: Thunder storm came up 1/2 past 7 from SW. Passed over 1/2 past 8
A few flashes of lightning seen late in the evening can not say from which direction the light came.
Several heavy claps of Thunder from a cloud in the south 3 pm
Very fine Aurora, commenced soon after twilight. Streamers formed first in the south and SE. Corona formed about 8 o'c with a brilliant display of red green and yellow streamers
Tremendous wind at 2 1/2 am with rain very heavy
3 1/4 pm violent gale with torrens of rain and hail, lasted but a few minutes
Fine aurora, at seven fine red streamers in the NE
